[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating compile-time features**\n\nI'm considering if testing a feature only at compile-time is sufficient. The TCK probably prefers a runtime pass for native features. It seems a better approach would be to support deeply interpolated values where placeholders might conflict with string parts. Using something like `Replacement.apply` can help avoid that. Also, I need to ensure that if interpolated expressions have side effects, the generated code evaluates them only once at the appropriate time. I'm reminded that proper evaluation order matters too!\n\n**Testing side effects in interpolation**\n\nI'm thinking about how to test an interpolation method that increments a counter and asserts once. But is supporting side effects really a feature? The public API's interpolation values don't seem to cover evaluation semantics. I might end up duplicating interpolation logic, which feels risky with native implementations. A useful feature could be ensuring fields with interpolated keys and values maintain member order. I need to test the `Json.obj` order to check this new functional feature!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0b54688ebe1c2c87016a3f906dcb0081938b1fe3356c29f942\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqP5CGRUXBs2IUOC5GwpmDTU84UumRgiJBXzsZ_SNo7Npy0KLJZEBkbItKnBaY_sFcZ1oYSDqJ53CQFC2cTKAlB7HFu3yfFiX9KNyXJurR2opxH66S0ciymqnJlUJL3Oe84l0pOcHggOCYrTr3obnA1hfL9SHm7lh-818ZnMzn6CS7YAQQH9NzlNfy6ryC9cQjjJNPcrzUnF7TSyoM9a72rnRMOFq6yOBs9kDriziKZDr5QF8bmqUxUYxXOiOErjAxnCo6IdSvj2NrgRHQ-cdWIH9K8SRsKWkIYVisrvltZZ7i-0EL3EyoRnJXvya2a9p46MJOWyO7DaAipVBI3Ys_VZQU9gzUd3dWUBqCkFYbcLeqjUx3DXbqR-SSPD7QTf8rz9Cf5qx-UoxzUpT3C4DWJR8jRZoO5MIb_l74bt5zvNvY5JKdPo9NBtCLnyoy2ms4LW_NYVFa9zSPCTOu59KeoHMDLgfAVq0p6NxnfUTrDXJZ8IKs-7nny9wm0phsVj4a3sNY-B4-6VN6iD5JzA4bygnlv0Vf4xt8Yd-aywA_DswmWdLeh5LXJnCzurH1iX67y7Q9-hKPjFDCrvsHkc1dfe__1KOSviTMFWKEB58ECxm2709v